In [5]:
def load_and_prep_image(filename, img_shape=224, scale=True):
    '''
    Function reads an image, turns it into a tensor and resize it to (224,224,3)

    Variables:
    filename (str) - name of file for target image
    img_shape (int) - image shape the model works with
    scale (bool) - whether scaling pixel values between 0 and 1 is necessary, based on model we're using
    '''

    # read in the image
    img = tf.io.read_file(filename)
    # decode it into a tensor
    img = tf.io.decode_image(img)
    # resize the image
    img = tf.image.resize(img, [img_shape, img_shape])
    if scale:
        # rescale image to between 0 and 1
        return img/255.0
    else:
        return img

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

for img in custom_food_image:

    # plot the image
    plt.figure()
    plt.imshow(img/255.) # normalize values
    plt.title(f'Prediction: {pred_class}, Probability: {pred_prob.max():.2f}')

Based on the results the model produced, I can sort of understand why they chose these predictions, more so for rice, less so for cherry tomato.

Rice was predicted as beignets, most likely due to the model flagging it's white colour for the icing sugar on the beignets. And you can see how much dusting the beignets get with icing sugar alone, making most of the food pure white.

Meat pie was predicted as apple pie, most likely due to how majority of pies all have a distinct pastry bowl and cover shape. It also didn't help how the pie pastry was not breached, therefore you cannot determine the type of filling is in it with just the pastry outside, however caveat to that is apple pies do have a very distinct criss cross pastry design on top where you can see through to the filling, while most meat pies come with a solid pastry lid.

Cherry tomato is a weird one, the only way I can think of it's prediction as a 'donut' is those dunkin donuts munchkins, or the tim horton's timbits, aka those doughnut holes. But it seems too red to be anything of matching to the pastry and it's colourfulness of the food.

Note: The pictures of the food were taken very unorthodox, and not presented as a dish on a plate with other sides and accessories. I simply pulled out whatever food objects I had at home and take a few quick pictures to speed up the process, but to also see how much I can stress the model. Even 2 of the food objects aren't really classified as dishes themselves, since the model has only been trained on dish types of food, with many contributing pieces and entrees, while mine is a bunch of singular food items that can be incorporated into a dish.

Given that, the model still made pretty good educational guesses.

2. Train a feature-extraction transfer learning model for 10 epoch, versus a model which used feature extraction for 5 epochs and fine-tuning for 5 epochs

We have already done the 5 feature extraction, 5 fine tuned model on the previous workbook, and saved it as well. So for this exercise, we only need to model train 10 epoch feature extraction. Once done, we can compare this via evaluation of test_data, in addition to visually compare/contrast their loss and accuracy curves while training 10 epochs.

The list of steps are as follows:

  1. Instantiate helper_functions for some quick easy functions to use during this exercise, rather than creating our own.
  2. Get train directory, and create our train dataset to be trained on
  3. Create an augmentation sequential model, which gives image data variety to the model
  4. Set up base model, and functional api model. Make sure all trainable features of base model is set to False, only leaving adam lr weights changeable
  5. Now evaluate them, and visually check and contrast both models with their loss and accuracy values between the graphs, and evaluation info

Let's create the augmentation sequential model, to give more variety of type of image data the model may recieve. (Also, this is so we can keep in line with previous experiments, as it is an independent variable that must be kept in control of, so we can truly see what transfer learning does, compared to transfer learning half, then fine tune half.)

In [18]:
# create augmentation model
from tensorflow.keras import layers
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential

data_augmentation = Sequential([
    layers.RandomFlip('horizontal'),
    layers.RandomRotation(0.2),
    layers.RandomZoom(0.2),
    layers.RandomHeight(0.2),
    layers.RandomWidth(0.2),
    # preprocessing.Rescaling(1./255) # keep for ResNet40V2, remove for EfficientNetB0 as they do this process automatically
], name='data_augmentation')

Now let's set up our base model and recreate the functional API model.

For our base model, we remove the top classified layer, as it is shaped entirely different to our data (it has 1000 categories), but have to make sure our input_size is stated, else the layers won't know what to expect,

Recreate our model, and add input layer as well, so all layers in our functional api needs to know the input_shape to expect, not just base model. Remember this is feature extracting, so no training weights on base model. Only thing that's changing freely are our augmentation model, and Adam weights when compiling.

Note: Trainable. freezes the weights, and Training freezes the normalized/dropout/scaled values, aka weights that pull the strings from behind.

Aka we have a model that predicts weight of potatoes in kilograms. Trainable is the data (potatoes, mushrooms) and Training is the scale (kilogram, pounds and ounces).

In [22]:
# setup base model and freeze its layers (our feature extractor)
base_model = tf.keras.applications.EfficientNetB0(include_top=False, weights='imagenet', input_shape=(224,224,3))
base_model.trainable = False # freeze our weights in layers

# setup model architecture with trainable top layer
inputs = layers.Input(shape=(224,224,3), name='input_layer') # shape of input image
x = data_augmentation(inputs) # augment our training images
x = base_model(x, training=False) # put base model in inference mode, so no scaling weights are updated - thus it is truly a feature extracting model
x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(name='global_average_pooling')(x) # pool the ouputs of base model into 1D data, so outputs can read them
outputs = layers.Dense(len(train_data_all_10_percent.class_names), activation='softmax', name='output_layer')(x) # create output, with same number of classes for model to use on predicting class
model = tf.keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

Let's plot out the training curve thru epochs.

In [26]:
plot_loss_curves(history_all_classes_10_percent)

And this is the following, 5 epoch transfer learning, and 5 epoch fine tuning curve graph:

When we visually compare both curves, we can see how the fine tuned version achieved better training loss and accuracy, comparative to full transfer learning model. This is based on the numbered axis compression, which is slightly more compressed on fine tune over transfer learning, and the line also seem to go a bit more lower.

However, both have very similar line tapering, indicating that this can likely be the pre-trained model's limiting factor, not because of the way we trained. They both have overfitted on the training data, the more epochs it is trained on, while test loss and accuracy has essentially flatlined, and may have even reversed improvements.

Based on what our eyes can see, it's very difficult to definitively prove which model is better, thus we will have to evaluate both models on the full test model, and see the loss and accuracy value between the two.

3. Recreate our first model (the feature extraction model) with mixed_precision turned on.

But first of all, what is mixed precision?

Mixed Precision is where the model uses a mix of float16 and float32. Some layers (especially matrix multiplications) run on float16, while others (like BatchNorm) stay in float32.

This helps with huge speedup in training with modern GPUs, lowers memory usage (allowing bigger batch sizes), and improves training stability.

You see most of it's benefit on training deep CNNs (EfficientNet, ResNet, Vision Transformers, etc.)

  1. Let's import mixed_precision, and set global policy to mixed_float16.
  2. Recreate our feature extraction model, but make sure output layer is float32.
  3. Recreate model compiling, and then begin training 10 epochs of the model.

So let's import mixed_precision and set up mixed_float16.

In [34]:

from tensorflow.keras import mixed_precision

mixed_precision.set_global_policy('mixed_float16')

Now recreate our model again - but make sure we name it different to avoid conflict with our previous model, and that output is also float32.

Why float32? It's due to how big the values get, once you reach the dense layer + softmax. float16 max value is 6.5e4, whilst float32 max value is 3.4e38. If the value is too big for float16 to read, then it would simply be treated as inf or NaN, which would break things very quickly.

In [36]:
# setup base mode again
base_model = tf.keras.applications.EfficientNetB0(include_top=False, weights='imagenet', input_shape=(224,224,3))
base_model.trainable=False

inputs = layers.Input(shape=(224,224,3), name='input_layer')
x = data_augmentation(inputs)
x = base_model(x, training=False)
x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(name='global_average_pooling')(x)

# keep output layer as float32
outputs = layers.Dense(len(train_data_all_10_percent.class_names), activation='softmax', dtype='float32', name='output_layer')(x)
model_mix_precise = tf.keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

I have aborted the training process, as the mixed_precision only causes longer training times for CPU, due to the way it is when being processed, therefore offering no benefit to my current setup.

From what ChatGPT has suggested, the speed up on modern GPU training can be 1.5 to 3 times faster, or even 2 to 4 times with larger batch sizes.

So the question is:

Does it make the model train faster?

It depends on your hardware. With modern GPUs, it will see some significant boosts in speed. But this is the opposite case for CPU only training.

Does it effect the accuracy or performance of our model?

This would be unsure, since I'm not keen on waiting hours for it to run on my setup. My thoughts based on what has been said, is that it doesn't change much in accuracy. The main benefit is the speed of training.

What's the advatanges of using mixed_precision training?

Much faster training, therefore you're able to complete any experiments and project at a faster rate, since there's less inbetween waiting for the model to finish training. But it's only advantageous if you have the right hardware to use mixed_precision, and it helps if you're able to install all the damn softwares and it's nit picky versions, to actually get tensorflow to recognize that you have a GPU on your PC.
